{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504335"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2322"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2322"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.38,0.11,0.07,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89469"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2322"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"},{"type":"tags","id":"2087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44942"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89469"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with facial trauma after being struck in the face during a sporting event. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His nasal dorsum is deviated to the right with associated bruising and swelling. The nasal septum is also deviated to the right. He has bilateral epistaxis. There are no other facial or neurological injuries identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is diagnosed with an acute nasal fracture and referred to the ear, nose and throat clinic. At review five days later, he reports ongoing nasal obstruction and deformity with minor epistaxis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and review in one month","Open surgical intervention within one week of the initial injury","Topical vasoconstrictors and nasal irrigation","Needle and syringe drainage via the patient\u0027s GP","Closed reduction via manual manipulation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a displaced nasal fracture requiring reduction. The nasal bone is the most commonly fractured facial bone. Assessment requires careful history and examination focusing on mechanism of injury, associated injuries, and exclusion of septal haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassure and review\u003C/strong\u003E in one month would miss the optimal window for reduction. After 2-3 weeks, the nasal bones begin to heal and become less mobile, making reduction more difficult and potentially requiring more invasive procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen surgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E within one week is too early, as facial swelling would make accurate reduction difficult. The optimal timing for reduction is between 7-14 days post-injury, when swelling has subsided but the bones remain mobile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical vasoconstrictors and nasal irrigation\u003C/strong\u003E may help manage symptoms like epistaxis and congestion but do not address the underlying anatomical deformity that requires reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle and syringe drainage\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for a septal haematoma, which is not present in this case. A septal haematoma is a surgical emergency requiring immediate drainage to prevent septal cartilage necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction via manual manipulation\u003C/strong\u003E at 7-14 days post-injury is the most appropriate management. This timing allows for resolution of acute swelling while the bones remain mobile enough for manipulation. The procedure is typically performed under local anaesthesia with intranasal cocaine or lidocaine plus epinephrine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A displaced nasal fracture should be reduced within 7-14 days after injury when swelling has subsided but bones remain mobile.","Clinical examination is the mainstay of assessment for nasal fractures, focusing on mechanism, complications, and excluding septal haematoma.","Early surgical intervention (\u003C7 days) should be avoided for nasal fractures as facial swelling can lead to suboptimal reduction."],"references":["Hoffmann JF. An Algorithm for the Initial Management of Nasal Trauma. Facial Plast Surg. 2015;31(3):183-193. doi:10.1055/s-0035-1555618 Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26126215/","Epstein S, Ettinger RE. Nasal and Naso-orbito-ethmoid Fractures. Semin Plast Surg. 2021;35(4):263-268. Published 2021 Sep 23. doi:10.1055/s-0041-1735791 Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8604621/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2322"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-09T20:18:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-09T20:18:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2322"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89469"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c